, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name, borne, according to legend, by a figure who gave her name to the River Liffey."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Llywarch","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional, now only occasionally used: compound of the god's name <i>Lugu-</i> (  see  Lleu  ) + Old Celtic <i>marcos</i> ‘horse’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Fychan\"","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Wife Llywarch \" Fychan\" Ap Llywarch x was born about 1174, in Wales, United Kingdom. She married Llywarch \"Fychan\" Ap Llywarch about 1200, in Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 5 sons."},"et":{"about 1174–":"umbes 1174–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1222–Male":"1222–Surnud","1224–Male":"1224–Surnud","1226–Male":"1226–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1174–Female":"1174–Surnud","1226":"1226","1224":"1224","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","about 1226":"umbes 1226","1222":"1222","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","about 1222":"umbes 1222","1174":"1174","about 1174":"umbes 1174","1170":"1170","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","of,Rhos ctf,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1174–":"noin 1174–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1222–Male":"1222–Kuollut","1224–Male":"1224–Kuollut","1226–Male":"1226–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1174–Female":"1174–Kuollut","1226":"1226","1224":"1224","Abt 1200":"noin 1200","about 1226":"noin 1226","1222":"1222","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","about 1222":"noin 1222","1174":"1174","about 1174":"noin 1174","1170":"1170","about 1230":"noin 1230",